#Causes - Q Fever - 1C33
Q fever is caused by bacteria known as coxiella burnetii (or c. burnetii). This bacteria generally spreads by animals infected by the bacteria. The most commonly affected animals, and those that pose the biggest risk to humans, are: Sheep, Cows, Goats, Domesticated pets, such as dogs, cats and guinea pigs.
#Diagnosis - Q Fever - 1C33
Q fever can be diagnosed using a blood test. Blood test: If the c. burnetii bacteria that cause Q fever is present in blood, then immune system (the bodyâ€™s natural defence system) will produce a type of protein called an antibody to kill them.
#Symptoms - Q Fever - 1C33
Incubation period is usually two to three weeks. The most common manifestation is mild flu-like symptoms with: Onset of fever, Malaise, Profuse perspiration, Severe headache, Myalgia (muscle pain), Joint pain, Loss of appetite, Upper respiratory problems, Dry cough.
#Overview - Q Fever - 1C33
Q fever is a bacterial infection caused by the coxiella burnetii bacteria. It causes flu-like symptoms such as a high temperature, muscle pain and headaches. The infection results from inhalation of a spore-like small cell variant, and from contact with the milk, urine, feces, vaginal mucus, or semen of infected animals. Rarely, the disease is also known as tick borne.
#Treatment - Q Fever - 1C33
Antibiotics can be used for Q fever like doxycycline or tetracycline. In pregnant women as doxycycline and ciprofloxacin are contraindicated in pregnancy. The preferred treatment is five weeks of co-trimoxazole.